<h1>From Robert Stewart</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Cresaps [Md.] August 4th 1758</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Last night 37 Waggons with Muskett Ball came here from Fort Frederick 18 of which were unloaded here and returns to Fort Frederick for more the other 19 proceeds to Fort Cumberland, Govr Sharpe desird Captain Ware Commandg the Escort to apply to me for a small Reinforcement to the Convoy now going to Fort Cumberland I have added a Serjeant &amp; 12 to it which makes it near 50 Effectives. Lieut. Pretter remains here with 7 Men &amp; no Provisions, he applied to me for a supply and as he has so few and these quite in want I have agreed to supply him till I receive your orders he informs me that the 19 Waggons thats now going up to Fort Cumberland is to return to morrow for the Ball left here and that he by Govr Sharpes orders has applied to you for an Escort for them<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0001-ptr">1</a>If you think proper I imagine it would be a good way to Releive the Grass Guard to morrow in place of next day, the Waggons to come down with new Guard &amp; to return Loaded with the old, which would save a Command for that purpose.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>Many of the Boxes are in very bad order and some of the Ball lost by their own acknowledgement.</p>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-05-02-pb-0369">[369]</span>
<p>I wrote by almost every opportunity thats gone to Winchester for these 3 weeks past for hair to Stuff our Saddles but could get none, by which many of the horses backs are almost ruind, our Jaunt to Rays Town added no less than six to that Number,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> the whole woud soon be hurt without I can remove the cause therefore sent off Serjeant Boltimore and Hencock last night to Winchester for hair and new Scabbards for the Swords which they are in great want off, this I hope youll approve off as its absolutely necessary.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
<p>If anything new or interesting has occurrd will be vastly obligd by your droping me a lineI beg you will offer my Complemts to Colo. Byrd &amp; the rest of the Gentn and beleive me ever to be With the highest Esteem &amp; greatest Deference My Dear Colonel Your most Affecte &amp; mos. Obt hble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Robert Stewart</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0292-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>Francis Ware was captain of one of the companies in the Maryland force. For the request that Lt. Henry Prather (spelled Pretter here) made to GW, see his letter of this date. See also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0297" class="document">GW to Bouquet, 6 August</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The guard for the horses of Stewarts troop and for the cattle belonging to the Virginia Regiment grazing in the vicinity of Cresaps Old Town came down from GWs camp at Fort Cumberland and was relieved periodically.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>In his return of the horse troop on 1 Aug. Stewart wrote, N.B. one of the Horses that went on Command to Pensylvania are lost, one lame &amp; two sore Back the rest in extreme bad order (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>). Stewarts returns indicate that ten of his men were on command as early as 13 July and only seven on 1 August. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0270&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0270-fn-0002#GEWN-02-05-02-0270-fn-0002" class="document">Stewart to GW, 25 July, n.2</a>. Bouquet wrote Forbes on 8 Aug. that three hundred saddles have been repaired, but we have no more wadding or hair to fill the rest (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Donald H. Kent et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;The Papers of Henry Bouquet&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Harrisburg, Pa., 1951-94. ]">Stevens, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Bouquet Papers</span></span>, 2:33539).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0292-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>Hencock may be Joseph Handcock who in 1757 was listed in GWs company (<a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0248" class="document">Roll of George Washingtons Company, 28 Aug. 1757</a><span class="choice deletion" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Deleted: ', printed above' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2014-11-06]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"><img alt="deletion" src="images/deletion_mark-trans.png" style="border:none;vertical-align: text-bottom; padding-right:2px"/></span>). Serjeant Boltimore is probably Christopher Baltimore, a soldier in Capt. Thomas Flemings company of the 2d Virginia Regiment.</p>

</div>
</div>
